{{Infobox member of the Knesset |image =תצלום של ערי ז'בוטינסקי.jpg |birth_date = 26 December 1910 |birth_place = [[Odessa]], [[Russian Empire]] |Year of Aliyah = 1919 |death_date = 6 June 1969 (aged 58) |death_place = [[Haifa]], [[Israel]] |Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 1951|1]] |party1 = [[Herut]] |partyyears1 = 1949–1951 |party2 = Independent |partyyears2 = 1951 }}
'''Eri Jabotinsky''' ({{Lang-he|ערי ז'בוטינסקי}}, also transliterated '''''Ari''''', {{Birth date|1910|12|26}} – {{Date of death|1969|6|6}}) was a [[Revisionist Zionism|Revisionist Zionist]] activist, [[Israel]]i politician and academic mathematician. He was the son of [[Ze'ev Jabotinsky]], the founder of the opposition movement within [[Zionism]] at the time, and later served in the Knesset between 1949 and 1951, as a member of the opposition [[Herut]] party of [[Menachem Begin]]. Following his break with the party, he pursued his academic career.
==Biography== Born in [[Odessa]], the Jabotinsky family made ''[[aliyah]]'' to [[Mandatory Palestine]] in 1919. Following the arrest of his father the following year, he left the country and moved to [[France]], where he attended high school in [[Paris]], and later earned a degree in electrical engineering. Between 1933 and 1935 he worked as an engineer in an aircraft factory. In 1935 he returned to Palestine, and worked as an engineer at the [[Naharayim]] power station in the [[Jordan Valley (Middle East)|Jordan Valley]]. [[File:Zeev Jabotinsky family.jpg|thumb|250px|Eri Jabotinsky (right) with his parents in the late 1920s]] A long-term member of Revisionism's [[Betar]] youth movement, he became one of its representative leaders in 1936, and joined its worldwide board two years later. With Betar and the party's military wing, [[Irgun]], he helped coordinate [[Aliyah Bet|illegal Jewish immigration]] into Palestine; he was temporarily arrested by the British authorities in 1940, and upon his release he moved to the [[United States]], where his father died suddenly about the same time. There, together with [[Hillel Kook]]'s 'Bergson Boys', [[Aryeh Ben-Eliezer]], [[Shmuel Merlin]] and [[Yitzhak Ben-Ami]], they founded the Emergency Committee to Save European Jewry,<ref>[https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/biography/beneli.html Aryeh Ben-Eliezer] Jewish Virtual Library</ref> among others. He briefly returned to Palestine, but was again arrested by the British and expelled for illegal activities in 1944.
Following [[Declaration of Independence (Israel)|Israel's independence]], he returned in 1948, and was elected to the [[Israeli legislative election, 1949|first Knesset]] the following year, as a member of the [[Herut]] party's list of candidates. On 20 February 1951 however, Jabotinsky and Hillel Kook left Herut, and sat as independents for the rest of the term, although the move was not recognised by the house committee;<ref>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/faction/eng/FactionHistoryAll_eng.asp Mergers and Splits Among Parliamentary Groups] Knesset website</ref> this followed on-going disagreements over the party’s direction and its new leadership by [[Menachem Begin]].
After leaving the Knesset, he was awarded a PhD in mathematics in 1957 from the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]. He also lectured on electricity theory at the [[Technion – Israel Institute of Technology|Technion]] between 1955 and his death in 1969.
He was the father-in-law of [[Anatoly Rubin]]
==Academic publications== *{{cite journal |author = Eri Jabotinsky |title = On the use of spherical means in hydrodynamics. Application to the study of the inception of turbulence |journal = Israel Journal of Mathematics |volume = 9 |year = 1971 |pages = 3–19 |issue = 1 |doi = 10.1007/BF02771614}} *{{cite journal |author = E. Jabotinsky |title = Universal relations between the elements of Grunsky's matrix |journal = Journal d'Analyse Mathématique |volume = 17 |year = 1966 |pages = 411–417 |issue = 1 |doi = 10.1007/BF02788667}} *{{cite journal |author=E. Jabotinsky |title=<math>l</math>-sequences for nonembeddable functions |journal=Proceedings of the American Mathematical Society |volume=17 |year=1966 |pages=738–738 |issue=3 |url=http://www.ams.org/journals/proc/1966-017-03/S0002-9939–1966-0192034-X/S0002-9939–1966-0192034-X.pdf |doi=10.1090/S0002-9939-1966-0192034-X }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} *{{cite journal |author=Eri Jabotinsky |title=Analytic Iteration |journal=Transactions of the American Mathematical Society |volume=108 |year=1963 |issue=3 |url=http://www.ams.org/journals/tran/1963-108-03/S0002-9947–1963-0155971-X/S0002-9947–1963-0155971-X.pdf |doi=10.2307/1993593 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} *{{cite journal |author = Eri Jabotinsky |title = Analytic iteration |journal = Transactions of the American Mathematical Society |volume = 108 |year = 1963 |pages = 457–457 |issue = 3 |doi = 10.1090/S0002-9947-1963-0155971-X}} *{{cite journal |author = Paul Erdös |author2 = Eri Jabotinsky |title = On analytic iteration |journal = Journal d'Analyse Mathématique |volume = 8 |year = 1960 |pages = 361–376 |issue = 1 |url = http://www.springerlink.com/index/r6k7417g74251451.pdf |doi = 10.1007/BF02786856}} *{{cite journal |author = Eri Jabotinsky |title = Representation of Functions by Matrices. Application to Faber Polynomials |journal = Proceedings of the American Mathematical Society |volume = 4 |year = 1953 |issue = 4 |doi = 10.2307/2032522}} *{{cite journal |author = Eri Jabotinsky |title = Representation of functions by matrices. Application to Faber polynomials |journal = Proceedings of the American Mathematical Society |volume = 4 |year = 1953 |pages = 546–546 |issue = 4 |doi = 10.1090/S0002-9939-1953-0059359-0}}
