{{unreferenced|date=September 2015}}
In algebra, the '''fixed-point subgroup''' <math>G^f</math> of an automorphism ''f'' of a [[group (mathematics)|group]] ''G'' is the [[subgroup]] of ''G'':
:<math>G^f = \{ g \in G \mid f(g) = g \}.</math>
More generally, if ''S'' is a set of automorphisms of ''G'' (i.e., a subset of the [[automorphism group]] of ''G''), then the set of the elements of ''G'' that are left fixed by every automorphism in ''S'' is a subgroup of ''G'', denoted by ''G''<sup>''S''</sup>.

For example, take ''G'' to be the group of invertible ''n''-by-''n'' real matrices and <math>f(g)=(g^T)^{-1}</math> (called the [[Cartan involution]]). Then <math>G^f</math> is the group <math>O(n)</math> of ''n''-by-''n'' [[orthogonal matrix|orthogonal matrices]].

To give an abstract example, let ''S'' be a subset of a group ''G''. Then each element of ''S'' can be thought of as an automorphism through conjugation. Then
:<math>G^S = \{ g \in G | sgs^{-1} = g \}</math>;
that is, the [[centralizer]] of ''S''.

