[[File:Helge Tverberg.jpg|thumb|220px|Helge Tverberg at [[Mathematical Research Institute of Oberwolfach|Oberwolfach]] in 1981]] '''Helge Arnulf Tverberg''' (born 6 March 1935) is a [[Norwegian people|Norwegian]] [[mathematician]]. He was a professor in the Mathematics Department at the [[University of Bergen]], his speciality being [[combinatorics]]; he retired at the mandatory age of seventy.
He was born in [[Bergen]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://meldinger.uib.no/engelsk.php?id=191101115828|title=Meet the mathematician, Helge Tverberg|date=November 22, 2001|publisher=University of Bergen}}</ref> He took the [[cand.real.]] degree at the University of Bergen in 1958, and the [[dr.philos.]] degree in 1968. He was a lecturer from 1958 to 1971 and professor from 1971 to his retirement in 2005. He was a visiting scholar at the [[University of Reading]] in 1966 and at the [[Australian National University]], in Canberra, from 1980 to 1981, 1987 to 1988 and in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|title=70 år 6. mars: Professor, dr. philos. Helge Arnulf Tverberg|agency=Norwegian News Agency|date=23 February 2005|language=Norwegian}}</ref> He is a member of the [[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnva.no/c26848/artikkel/vis.html?tid=27624|title=Gruppe 1: Matematiske fag |publisher=[[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=29 October 2009}}</ref>
Tverberg, in 1965, proved a result on intersection patterns of partitions of [[point configuration]]s that has come to be known as [[Tverberg's partition theorem]]. It inaugurated a new branch of [[combinatorial geometry]], with many variations and applications. An account by [[Günter M. Ziegler]] of Tverberg's work in this direction appeared in the issue of the Notices of the American Mathematical Society for April, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ams.org/notices/201104/rtx110400550p.pdf|title=3N Colored Points in a Plane}}</ref>
